Rationale

Meta-analysis of [GASP+U-BIOPRED+UKB], GERA and Chang. et al.cohorts for moderate-to-severe and severe asthma phenotype and use this summary statistics for a replication analysis for UK Biobank severe asthma GWAS.

    tail -n +2 > /home/n/nnp5/PhD/PhD_project/Post_GWAS/input/${pheno}_suggestive_sentinels.snplist

    > /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/multiallelic.snps

#run cgta-condcojo:
for line in {2..69}
do
SNP=$(awk -v row="$line" -F "\t" ' NR == row {print $1 } ' ${PATH_OUT}/${PHENO}_pvalsuggestive_sentinel_variants.txt )
chr=$(awk -v row="$line" -F "\t" ' NR == row {print $2 } ' ${PATH_OUT}/${PHENO}_pvalsuggestive_sentinel_variants.txt )

#filter out for sentinel region only:
if [[ $SNP == "rs762279794" ]]
then
#remove the duplicated variants keeping the sentinel:
    module load plink2
    plink2 \
        --bfile /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/${pheno}_plink_file_v3_chr${chr} \
        --rm-dup force-first \
        --maf 0.01 \
        --make-bed --out /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/${pheno}_plink_file_v3_chr${chr}
    module unload plink2; module load plink
    plink \
        --bfile /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/${pheno}_plink_file_v3_chr${chr} \
        --snp ${SNP} \
        --window ${window_size} \
        --maf 0.01 \
        --make-bed --out /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/${pheno}_suggestive_plink_file_v3_chr${chr}_${SNP}
else
    plink \
        --bfile /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/${pheno}_plink_file_v3_chr${chr} \
        --snp ${SNP} \
        --window ${window_size} \
        --maf 0.01 \
        --make-bed --out /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/${pheno}_suggestive_plink_file_v3_chr${chr}_${SNP}
fi

/home/r/rja34/bin/gcta_1.90.2beta/gcta64 \
     --bfile /scratch/gen1/nnp5/REGENIE_assoc/tmp_data/${pheno}_suggestive_plink_file_v3_chr${chr}_${SNP} \

Code: REGENIE_assoc/src/broad_phenotype/Create_oddsratio.R

#!/usr/bin/env Rscript


suppressMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressMessages(library(data.table))

args = commandArgs(trailingOnly=TRUE)

input_file = args[1]
output_file = args[2]


#input:
sumstat <- read.table(input_file,header=T)

#create odds_ratio ci_lower ci_upper
sumstat$odds_ratio <- exp(sumstat$LOG_ODDS)
sumstat$ci_lower <- exp(sumstat$LOG_ODDS - qnorm(0.975)*sumstat$se)
sumstat$ci_upper <- exp(sumstat$LOG_ODDS + qnorm(0.975)*sumstat$se)

#create unique column:
sumstat$'OR_95_CI' <- paste0(format(round(sumstat$odds_ratio,2),nsmall=2)," [",format(round(sumstat$ci_lower,2),nsmall=2),"-",format(round(sumstat$ci_upper,2),nsmall=2),"]")

#direction of effect:
sumstat <- sumstat %>% mutate(direction_of_effect=ifelse(sumstat$LOG_ODDS > 0, "+","-"))

write.table(sumstat,output_file,sep="\t",quote=F,row.names=F)

We ran a replication analysis for independent variants that reached genome-wide suggestive threshold (p-value < 5 x 10-6) in UK Biobank GWAS. To obtain the list of variants, I filtered all variants with p-value < 5 x 10-6; I selected the sentinel variants for 1Mb regions; and then I ran a conditional analysis in a region of 2Mb form the sentinel variants to identify any additional independent signals. If needed, I converted the genomic position from build 37 to build 38. I obtained a total of 67 variants that were used to run association analysis in the other cohorts.

Individual GWAS on different cohorts

This list of variants were used to run a genome-wide association analysis in three cohorts:

*GERA: Resource for Genetic Epidemiology Research on Aging (1)

*GASP: Genetics of Asthma Severity & Phenotypes (2)

*U-BIOPRED: Unbiased Biomarkers for the Prediction of Respiratory Disease Outcomes (3)

*Chang et al.: seq-GWAS with clinical trials participants of moderate-to-severe asthma (4)

GERA analysis has been conducted by collaborators Sharon Lutz, Kirsten Voorhies and Ann Wu. I performed the GWAS on GASP and U-BIOPRED; in this case, I also impute the data using TopMed reference genome and the Mighigan imputation server.

GERA

The case/control criteria was designed to be as similar as possible to UK Biobank phenotype:

  • Cases: asthma (from diagnosis and self-report) AND ICS and other asthma medication or exacerbations

  • Controls: No asthma AND No asthma medications

They used the following inclusion and exclusion criteria:

  1. Non-Hispanic white (NHW) participants with genetic data (67,820)
  2. NHW participants without COPD, chronic bronchitis, emphysema (61,716)
  3. Case or control criteria (23,087)
  4. Case/controls with values for covariates age and sex (22,970)

They obtained 6,598 cases and 16,372 control for which they ran a GWAS in plink with covariates: first 5 PCs, sex, age (mean centered, divided by sd(age)), age (mean centered, divided by sd(age)) squared.
They were able to run the association for 58 variants. Nine variants were not present in their genomic data; for these, they run association in the region of +/- 1,000bp from the missing SNP.
I then prepared the data for the meta-analysis. For variants analysed with proxies, I checked that the effect alleles of the discovery variant and its proxy were in the same haplotype; if not, I flipped the log odds ratio sign.

Code: src/GERA_for_meta.R

#!/usr/bin/env Rscript

#Create metasoft input from GERA 'severe asthma;' summary statistics


suppressMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressMessages(library(data.table))
suppressMessages(library(readxl))

args = commandArgs(trailingOnly=TRUE)

GERA_sumstat <- fread(args[1])
GERA_proxy <- fread(args[2])
output_file <- args[3]

#GERA_sumstat:
#create ID:
GERA_sumstat$ID <- paste0(GERA_sumstat$snpid,"_",GERA_sumstat$V3)
#select cols:
GERA_sumstat <- GERA_sumstat %>% select(snpid,V3,LOG_ODDS_GERA,LOG_ODDS_GERA_SE)
colnames(GERA_sumstat)[1] <- "SNP_UKB"
colnames(GERA_sumstat)[2] <- "SNP_GERA"

#GERA proxy
#calculate LOG_ODDS:
colnames(GERA_proxy)[4] <- "LOG_ODDS_GERA_SE"
GERA_proxy$LOG_ODDS_GERA <- log(GERA_proxy$V3)
GERA_proxy <- GERA_proxy %>% select(V1, V2,LOG_ODDS_GERA,LOG_ODDS_GERA_SE)
colnames(GERA_proxy)[1] <- "SNP_UKB"
colnames(GERA_proxy)[2] <- "SNP_GERA"

#Combine for metasoft:
GERA <- rbind(GERA_sumstat, GERA_proxy)

#Save file:
fwrite(GERA,output_file,sep=" ",quote=FALSE,row.names=FALSE,col.names=T,na="NA")

GASP, U-BIOPRED, and UKBiobank

Genetic data

U-BIOPRED individuals were genotyped with Affymetrix Axiom UK Biobank array.
GASP individuals came from two different genotyping array:

  • AirP-UoNAX: Affymetrix Axiom UK Biobank array;

  • AUGOSA: Affymetrix Axiom UK BiLEVE array
    UK Biobank was used for controls. In this biobank, genotyping was completed using Affymetrix Axiom UK Biobank array and Affymetrix Axiom UK BiLEVE array.
    Altogether, two different genotyping arrays were used.
    Imputation in UK Biobank was performed using the Haplotype Reference Consortium (HRC) (5).

Code: src/GWAS_UBIOPRED_GASP/create_pheno_age_sex.R

#!/usr/bin/env Rscript

suppressMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressMessages(library(data.table))

cases <- fread("/scratch/gen1/nnp5/Post_GWAS/tmp_data/all_cases_sex_age")
controls <- fread("/scratch/gen1/nnp5/Post_GWAS/tmp_data/all_controls_sex_age")

cases <- cases %>% mutate(sex=ifelse(cases$sex == 'male', 1,
                                      ifelse(cases$sex == 'MALE', 1,
                                      ifelse(cases$sex == 'female',0, cases$sex))))

controls <- controls %>% mutate(sex=ifelse(controls$sex == 'male', 1, ifelse(controls$sex == 'female',0, controls$sex)))

female_cases_count <- as.numeric(summary(as.factor(cases$sex))[1])*5
male_cases_count <- as.numeric(summary(as.factor(cases$sex))[2])*5

female_controls <- controls %>% filter(sex == 0)
female_controls <- female_controls[1:female_cases_count,1]

male_controls <- controls %>% filter(sex == 1)
male_controls <- male_controls[1:male_cases_count,1]

controls_eid <- rbind(male_controls,female_controls)

controls_ratio <- controls %>% filter(controls$ID %in% controls_eid$ID)

cases_controls <- rbind(cases, controls_ratio)

summary(as.factor(cases_controls$pheno)) # ok, these are the number we want
write.table(cases_controls,"/scratch/gen1/nnp5/Post_GWAS/tmp_data/cases_controls_sex_age",
row.names = FALSE, col.names = TRUE ,quote=FALSE, sep=" ", na = "NA")

#little bit for descriptive analysis for age and sex:
print("Cases and control - sex count")
table(cases_controls$sex, cases_controls$pheno)

print("Cases and control - mean age according to sex")
cases_controls %>% group_by(pheno, sex) %>% summarise(MeanAge=mean(age,na.rm=T)) %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = pheno,values_from=MeanAge)

print("Cases and control - standard deviation age according to sex")
cases_controls %>% group_by(pheno, sex) %>% summarise(SDAge=sd(age,na.rm=T)) %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = pheno,values_from=SDAge)

Phenotype data for the moderate-to-severe study (6), were stored in /data/gen1/AIRPROM/assoc/airprom_pheno_array.txt. After checking they had genotype data, I filtered cases defined as severe in GASP or U-BIOPRED. For controls, I included only genotyped individuals as well and controls from U-BIOPRED and from UK Biobank. For the latter dataset, I included European ancestry controls as defined by my discovery analysis but not used for it, using /data/gen1/UKBiobank_500K/severe_asthma/Noemi_PhD/data/demo_EUR_pheno_cov_broadasthma.txt. Controls were sex matched with the cases with a ratio of 1:5 case-controls.
I also need to retrieve age and sex as they were not present in airprom_pheno_array.txt for cases. I used different file sources for this step, all reported in the code.
The dataset includes a total of 12,498 individuals: 2,083 cases (1,365 females (65.5%), 718 males) and 10,415 controls (6,825 females (65.6%), 3590 males).

Code: src/GWAS_UBIOPRED_GASP/ubio_gasp_PCs.sh

#!/bin/bash

#Principal Components calculation for UBIOPRED, GASP, UK-BIOBANK severe asthma GWAS.

tmp_data="/scratch/gen1/nnp5/Post_GWAS/tmp_data"
PATH_wd="/home/n/nnp5/PhD/PhD_project/Post_GWAS"
cd ${PATH_wd}

#Genotype data:
#Start from the input file for imputation in the plink format:
#bim, bed, fam: /scratch/gen1/nnp5/Post_GWAS/tmp_data/all_overlapping.bim/bed/fam

module load plink

#prune variants:
#--geno 0.05 --maf 0.01  already done as filter before imputation:
plink --bfile ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping \
    --indep-pairwise 50 5 0.2 --out ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.filtered

plink --bfile ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping \
    --extract ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.filtered.prune.in \
    --make-bed \
    --out ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned

#check for duplicated variants and remove if any:
plink --bfile ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned  \
    --list-duplicate-vars \
    --out ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.missnp
#in this case I do not have duplicated variants, I think they will removed from previous QC:
wc -l ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.missnp.dupvar

# ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned is the file to use for PCA calculation
##PCA with n-PCs as the number of min(samples,variants):
mkdir ${tmp_data}/GASP_UBIO_UKB_imputed/PCA
plink --bfile ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned \
    --pca \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GASP_UBIO_UKB_imputed/PCA/all_overlapping.pruned.plink.pca


rm all_overlapping.filtered.* \
    ${tmp_data}/prune.* \
    ${tmp_data}/prune.out \
    ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.fam \
    ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.bim \
    ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.bed \
    ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.nosex
    ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.log \
    ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping.pruned.missnp.* \

I then calculated the genetic Principal Components (PCs) using 319,030 genotyped variants with genotyping rate of 0.996 among 12,498 individuals. I used plink v1.90b3.

#!/usr/bin/env Rscript

colnames(fam_ID) <- c("FID", "IID")
pheno_PCs_fam_ordered <- inner_join(fam_ID, pheno_PCs, by= "IID")


write.table(pheno_PCs_fam_ordered,"/home/n/nnp5/PhD/PhD_project/Post_GWAS/input/ubio_gasp_gwas/pheno_cov_ubio_gasp_ukb.txt",
row.names = FALSE, col.names = TRUE ,quote=FALSE, sep=" ", na = "NA")

Lastly, I merged the phenotype with the PCs file to obtain the final phenotype and covariate file for the association analysis.

Imputation

Thanks to discussions with colleagues, we decided to impute the share genotyped data among the four genetic sources for this analysis. they previously observed that imputation from same panel but from a different set of genotyped data can cause spurious association results.
Thus, after defining cases and controls, I retrieve the genotype data for all of them, combined together, filter for good quality. I obtained 576,917 shared good quality SNPs for 12,498 samples (22 chromosomes). I used this data as input for imputation. Code: src/GASP_UBIOPRED_UKB_imputation.sh

To validate the good quality of the results, I run some post-imputation analyses.
Firstly, I looked into the info score according to three MAF bins: common variant (MAF >= 0.05), low-frequency variants (0.05 < MAF <= 0.01), and rare variants (MAF < 0.01). Common and low-frequency variants were well imputed, while majority of rare variants were bad imputed (Figure 1).

Figure 1. Info imputation score frequency according to MAF bins.


I zoomed into the rare variants and excluded the ultra-rare variants, defined as MAF < 0.001 (Figure 2). Rare variants showed a good imputation score overall; ultra-rare variants remained bad imputed for the majority of them (Figure 2).

Figure 2. Info imputation score for rare and ultra-rare only variants.


In conclusion, the imputation showed good quality data for common, low and rare frequency variants. I will run the association analysis with variants with INFO > 0.3 and MAF>= 0.01; therefore the imputation data can be used as confirmed by the quality checks.

Code: src/GWAS_UBIOPRED_GASP/liftover_and_plink_QC_preregenie.sh

#!/bin/bash

#LifOver genotyped data since imputed data are in Build38. Then, QC for link file for REGENIE step 1

tmp_data="/scratch/gen1/nnp5/Post_GWAS/tmp_data"
PATH_wd="/home/n/nnp5/PhD/PhD_project/Post_GWAS"
software="/home/n/nnp5/software"
cd ${PATH_wd}
mkdir ${tmp_data}/GUU

#LiftOver form Build37 to Build38
#split in chromosome:
module load plink2
for chr in {1..22}; do \
plink2 \
    --bfile ${tmp_data}/all_overlapping \
    --chr $chr --make-bed \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/all_overlapping_${chr}; \
done

##create ped file:
#GUU: gasp, ubiopred, biobank
for chr in {1..22}; do \
${software}/plink2 \
    --bfile ${tmp_data}/GUU/all_overlapping_${chr} \
    --export ped \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr};
done

##liftover:
for chr in {1..22}; do \
python ${software}/liftOverPlink/liftOverPlink.py \
    -m ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}.map \
    -p ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}.ped \
    -o ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38 \
    -c ${software}/hg19ToHg38.over.chain.gz \
    -e ${software}/liftOver;
done

##remove bad lifted/unlifted variants
for chr in {1..22}; do \
python ${software}/liftOverPlink/rmBadLifts.py \
    --map ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38.map \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_good_lifted \
    --log ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_bad_lifted.dat;
done

for chr in {1..22}; do \
cut -f 2 ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_bad_lifted.dat > ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_to_exclude.dat;
cut -f 4 ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38.bed.unlifted | sed "/^#/d" >> ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_to_exclude.dat;
done


#Remove the alternative contig: TO DO SPECIFIC TO EACH STUDY
#alternative contig in chromosome 1,4,7,8,14,17,19,22:
for chr in 1 7 8 17 19 22; do \
contig_to_exclude=$(grep "_alt\|_random" ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38.map | awk -F "\t" '{print $1}' | tr '\n' ' ');
${software}/plink2 \
    --pedmap ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38 \
    --make-pgen \
    --sort-vars \
    --allow-extra-chr --not-chr $contig_to_exclude \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted \
    --exclude ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_to_exclude.dat;
${software}/plink2 \
    --pfile ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted \
    --make-bed \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted;
done

for chr in 2 3 4 5 6 9 10 11 12 13 14 15 16 18 20 21; do \
${software}/plink2 \
    --pedmap ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38 \
    --make-pgen \
    --sort-vars \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted \
    --exclude ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_to_exclude.dat;
${software}/plink2 \
    --pfile ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted \
    --make-bed \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted;
done

#QC in plink:
for chr in {2..22}
do echo "${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted.bed ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted.bim ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_${chr}_b38_lifted.fam" >> ${tmp_data}/GUU/list_plink_files
done

module load plink
plink --bed ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_1_b38_lifted.bed \
    --bim ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_1_b38_lifted.bim \
      --fam ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_1_b38_lifted.fam \
      --merge-list ${tmp_data}/GUU/list_plink_files \
      --allow-no-sex \
    --make-bed --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_all_b38_lifted


module load plink2
plink2 --bfile ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_all_b38_lifted \
    --maf 0.01 --mac 100 --geno 0.1 --hwe 1e-15 \
    --mind 0.1 \
    --write-snplist --write-samples --no-id-header \
    --out ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_all_b38_geno_qc &&

cp ${tmp_data}/GUU/guu_all_b38_geno_qc.id ${PATH_wd}/input/ubio_gasp_gwas/

Since the genotype file and the imputed files are with different genomic build, I converted the genotype data into build 38 and then I applied the quality control in plink needed to run REGENIE step1.
I used liftOverPlink which is a tool to efficiently convert plink file format from a genomic build to another (link: https://github.com/sritchie73/liftOverPlink). I started from 661,202 genotyped variants and I was able to successfully convert 660,892 variants in Build38, missing 310 variants.
After plink filters (maf 0.01; mac; 100; geno 0.1; hwe 1e-15; mind 0.1), I obtained 582,895 good quality variants.

#Plot inflation plot with qqman package and qq() function.
plot.qqplot <- function(pval_vec,title){
           filename = paste0("output/Q-Q_plot_",title,".png")
           plot_title = paste0("Q-Q plot ",title)
           png(filename, width = 480, height = 480, units = "px", pointsize = 12, bg = "white")
               print(qq(pval_vec, main = plot_title, xlim = c(0,27), ylim = c(0,27), cex.axis = 1, cex = 1, las = 1)) #function from qqman library
               dev.off()
}

# Create a Manhattan plot from a data frame containing the results of
# a GEMMA association analysis.
plot.Manha <- function (dataset,test_type,title) {
          colnames(dataset) <- c("SNP","CHR","BP","P") #the Manhattan function needs this format
              filename <- paste0("output/Manhattan_plot_",title,".png")
              plot_title = paste0("Manhattan plot ",title)
          png(filename, width = 3200, height = 550, units = "px", pointsize = 12, bg = "white")
          manhattan(dataset, main = title, col = c("lightblue","blue3"), chrlabs = as.character(c(1:22)), ylim=c(0,25),
          cex = 1.5, cex.axis = 1.5, suggestiveline = F, genomewideline = F, cex.lab = 1.5)
          #function from qqman library
          abline(h=-log10(0.00000005),lty="dashed",col="black")
          abline(h=-log10(0.000005),lty="solid",col="black")
          dev.off()
}





#Estimate lambda using pval:
lambda_func <- function(pval,title){
        filename <- paste0("output/lambda_",title,".txt")
        pval <- qnorm(pval/2)
        lambda_frompval = round(median(pval^2,na.rm=T)/qchisq(0.5,df=1),2)
        write.table(lambda_frompval,filename,col.names="lambda",row.names=F)
        return
        lambda_frompval
}














# Create a simple Manhattan plot from a data frame containing the
# results of a GEMMA association analysis, in which p-values are
# plotted against base-pair positions (in Mb).
plot.region.pvalues <- function (gwscan, size = 1) {

  # Convert the p-values to the -log10 scale.
  gwscan <- transform(gwscan,p_lrt = -log10(p_lrt))

  # Convert the positions to the Megabase (Mb) scale.
  gwscan <- transform(gwscan,ps = ps/1e6)
  
  # Create a Manhattan plot.
  return(ggplot(gwscan,aes(x = ps,y = p_lrt)) +
         geom_point(color = "darkblue",size = size,shape = 20) +
         labs(x = "base-pair position (Mb)",y = "-log10 p-value") +
         theme_cowplot(font_size = 10) +
         theme(axis.line = element_blank()))
}

selectSentinels <- function(data.dt) {
    regions.list <- list()
    while(nrow(data.dt) > 0) {
        top.dt <- data.dt[ which.min(pval) ]
        regions.list[[top.dt$snpid]] <- top.dt
        data.dt <- data.dt[ b37chr != top.dt$b37chr
            | bp <= top.dt$bp - WIDTH
            | bp >= top.dt$bp + WIDTH ]
    }
    rbindlist(regions.list)
}


tier.dt <- fread(tier_file,header=T)
tier.dt <- tier.dt %>% filter(pval <= p_val_thresh)
sentinels.dt <- selectSentinels(tier.dt)
sentinels.dt <- sentinels.dt %>% arrange(b37chr)
write.table(sentinels.dt, paste0("output/",pheno,pheno_2,"_sentinel_variants.txt"), row.names=F, quote=F, sep="\t")

#!/usr/bin/env Rscript


suppressMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressMessages(library(data.table))

args = commandArgs(trailingOnly=TRUE)

input_file = args[1]
output_file = args[2]


#input:
sumstat <- read.table(input_file,header=T)

#create odds_ratio ci_lower ci_upper
sumstat$odds_ratio <- exp(sumstat$LOG_ODDS)
sumstat$ci_lower <- exp(sumstat$LOG_ODDS - qnorm(0.975)*sumstat$se)
sumstat$ci_upper <- exp(sumstat$LOG_ODDS + qnorm(0.975)*sumstat$se)

#create unique column:
sumstat$'OR_95_CI' <- paste0(format(round(sumstat$odds_ratio,2),nsmall=2)," [",format(round(sumstat$ci_lower,2),nsmall=2),"-",format(round(sumstat$ci_upper,2),nsmall=2),"]")

#direction of effect:
sumstat <- sumstat %>% mutate(direction_of_effect=ifelse(sumstat$LOG_ODDS > 0, "+","-"))

write.table(sumstat,output_file,sep="\t",quote=F,row.names=F)

I then prepared the data for the meta-analysis. For variants analysed with proxies, I checked that the effect alleles of the discovery variant and its proxy were in the same haplotype; if not, I flipped the log odds ratio sign.

guu_sumstat_matched <- guu_sumstat_matched %>% filter(SNP_GUU != "NA")

colnames(guu_sumstat)[1] <- "SNP_GUU"
colnames(guu_sumstat)[2] <- "CHR"
guu_sumstat_matched_LOGODDS <- left_join(guu_sumstat_matched,guu_sumstat, by = c("SNP_GUU","CHR"))

#Create logOR and flip sign if some proxies have effect allele in opposite haplotype:
guu_sumstat_matched_LOGODDS <- guu_sumstat_matched_LOGODDS %>% mutate(LOG_ODDS_update=ifelse(guu_sumstat_matched_LOGODDS$TO_FLIP == 1, -(guu_sumstat_matched_LOGODDS$LOG_ODDS), guu_sumstat_matched_LOGODDS$LOG_ODDS))


#Filter cols for metasoft:

colnames(guu_for_metasoft)[3] <- "LOG_ODDS_GUU"
colnames(guu_for_metasoft)[4] <- "LOG_ODDS_SE_GUU"

#Save file:
fwrite(guu_for_metasoft,output_file,sep=" ",quote=FALSE,row.names=FALSE,col.names=T,na="NA")

Code: src/create_metasoft_input_3cohorts_proxywise.R

#!/usr/bin/env Rscript

#Create metasoft input from the 3 cohorts taking into accoutn of multiple proxies for some variants:


suppressMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressMessages(library(data.table))
suppressMessages(library(readxl))

args = commandArgs(trailingOnly=TRUE)

ukb_snp_file <- args[1]
gera_file <- args[2]
guu_file <- args[3]
chang_file <- args[4]
output_file <- args[5]

ukb_snp <- read_excel(ukb_snp_file, sheet ="SNPID_in_metaanalysis", skip = 1)

#gera already has all the variants for hte meta-analysis. no need to add others.
gera_meta <- fread(gera_file)

#find all the variants for guu:
guu <- fread(guu_file)
guu_meta <- guu %>% filter(snpid %in% ukb_snp$SNP_GUU) %>% select(snpid, LOG_ODDS, se)
colnames(guu_meta) <- c("SNP_GUU","LOG_ODDS_GUU","LOG_ODDS_SE_GUU")

#find all the variants for chang:
chang <- fread(chang_file)
chang_meta <- chang %>% filter(SNP %in% ukb_snp$SNP_CHANG)
chang_meta$LOG_ODDS_chang <- log(chang_meta$OR)
chang_meta <- chang_meta %>% select(SNP, LOG_ODDS_chang, SE)
colnames(chang_meta) <- c("SNP_CHANG","LOG_ODDS_chang","LOG_ODDS_SE_chang")

#unify the dfs:
gera_meta_ukb <- left_join(ukb_snp,gera_meta,by=c("SNP_GERA","SNP_UKB"))
guu_gera_meta_ukb <- left_join(gera_meta_ukb,guu_meta,by=c("SNP_GUU"))
chang_guu_gera_meta_ukb <- left_join(guu_gera_meta_ukb,chang_meta,by=c("SNP_CHANG"))
chang_guu_gera_meta_ukb$ID <- paste0(chang_guu_gera_meta_ukb$SNP_UKB,";",chang_guu_gera_meta_ukb$SNP_GERA,";",chang_guu_gera_meta_ukb$SNP_GUU,";",chang_guu_gera_meta_ukb$SNP_CHANG)

metasoft_input <- chang_guu_gera_meta_ukb %>% select(ID,LOG_ODDS_GERA,LOG_ODDS_GERA_SE,LOG_ODDS_GUU,LOG_ODDS_SE_GUU,LOG_ODDS_chang, LOG_ODDS_SE_chang)

#Save file:
fwrite(metasoft_input,output_file,sep=" ",quote=FALSE,row.names=FALSE,col.names=F,na="NA")

Code: src/Disc_vs_meta_sumstat.R

#!/usr/bin/env Rscript

#Create dataset with GWAS sumstat and Meta-analsysis sumstat


suppressMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressMessages(library(data.table))
suppressMessages(library(readxl))
discovery <- fread("/home/n/nnp5/PhD/PhD_project/Post_GWAS/output/UKBiobank_severeasthma_sentinel_suggestive_to_replicate.txt") %>%
    select(c(snpid,chr,pos_b37,pos_b38,EA,NEA,pval,odds_ratio,ci_lower,ci_upper))
colnames(discovery)[1] <- "SNP_UKB"

meta <- fread("/home/n/nnp5/PhD/PhD_project/Post_GWAS/output/sevasthma_metasoft_output_3cohorts.txt") %>%
    select(c("RSID", "#STUDY", "BETA_RE","STD_RE","PVALUE_RE2","I_SQUARE"))
meta$OR_META <- exp(as.numeric(meta$BETA_RE))
meta$ci_lower_META <- exp(meta$BETA_RE - qnorm(0.975)*meta$STD_RE)
meta$ci_upper_META <- exp(meta$BETA_RE + qnorm(0.975)*meta$STD_RE)
meta <- meta %>% separate(RSID, c("SNP_UKB", "SNP_GERA", "SNP_GUU", "SNP_CHANG"), sep=";")

discovery_meta <- left_join(discovery,meta,by="SNP_UKB") %>% select(SNP_UKB,chr,pos_b37,pos_b38,EA,NEA,pval,odds_ratio,ci_lower,ci_upper,PVALUE_RE2,OR_META,ci_lower_META,ci_upper_META,"#STUDY",I_SQUARE,SNP_GERA,SNP_GUU,SNP_CHANG)
discovery_meta <- discovery_meta %>% mutate(concordance=ifelse(((discovery_meta$odds_ratio < 0 & discovery_meta$OR_META < 0) | (discovery_meta$odds_ratio > 0 & discovery_meta$OR_META > 0)), "+", "-"))
#save into the xlsx files for report:
fwrite(discovery_meta, "/home/n/nnp5/PhD/PhD_project/Post_GWAS/output/Disc_VS_Meta_sumstat", quote=FALSE,row.names=FALSE,col.names=T,na="NA")

For some variants, I used proxies that are different in the three cohorts. Therefore, I checked that for each variant I was taking the same proxy; when not possible, I used different proxy and ran the meta-analysis in each proxy (present in at least two studies).

I used two Bonferroni corrected p-values:

  • Bonferroni a: N. genome-wide sentinel variants : 0.05/14 = 3.57 x 10-3

  • Bonferroni b. N. suggestive sentinel variants : 0.05/67 = 7.46 x 10-4

Results

I was able to meta-analysed 61 out of 67 suggestive significant variants. Twenty-five variants showed evidence of replication in the meta-analysis with Bonferroni a, among which 13 genome-wide sentinel variants. With Bonferroni b, 22 variants were replicated, 12 were genome-wide sentinel variants.
Interestingly, the locus on chromosome 3 replicated at Bonferroni p-value, and it has been found associated with adult onset asthma in a meta-analysis of UK Biobank and Finn-Genn within the GBMI asthma study with rs11130234 [7] () in strong LD (R2 0.968) with rs778801698. Also rs11130234 has been mapped into RBM6 gene.

Conclusion

Thirteen sentinel variants replicated in the meta-analysis.
Regarding the novel locus on chromosome 3, it replicated at a nominal threshold only. However, we found evidence of association from the GBMI study [7].
RBM6 is a protein binding protein and this protein family has been of interested for asthma amf function in asthma still needs to be discovered.
A recent paper showed the importance of RBM3 into the cell activation and inflammation for innate lymphoid cells (ILC) through cysteinyl leukotriene 1 receptor (CysLT1R) [8].
For this reason, we think it is worth it investigating this region with fine-mapping and functional follow-up analyses.
